<TEXT>
members of a labor union burned an 
american flag and shouted slogans on wednesday to protest a new 
agreement on us military bases 
president corazon aquino dismissed criticism of the accord 
signed monday in washington by foreign secretary raul manglapus and 
us secretary of state george shultz and the largest political 
party in the philippines congress pledged to support it 
about 150 members of the leftist may first movement labor 
alliance burned an american flag near the us embassy shouting 
slogans assailing us foreign policy as they carried banners 
against the bases riot police prevented them from marching to the 
embassy grounds and they dispersed peacefully 
the agreement allows the united states to maintain six bases 
here until 1991 in return for 962 million in aid over the final 
two years of the pact 
but critics charged that the government settled for too little 
compensation filipino negotiators had demanded 12 billion 
annually 
i knew that it would not get total acceptance mrs aquino 
said of the agreement but i still believe secretary manglapus 
did a very commendable job and that certainly it is a big 
improvement from the previous bases agreement 
opposition sen juan ponce enrile said the agreement showed that 
mrs aquino had secretly decided to work for extending the bases 
even after their lease expires in september 1991 
the terms contained in the justconcluded agreement strongly 
indicate to us that the aquino regime will continue to foist upon 
our people this onerous burden of a military presence on philippine 
soil he said 
the united states had been paying 180 million a year for use of 
clark air base subic bay naval base and four smaller installations 
the proaquino struggle of the democratic filipino which claims 
151 out of 225 legislators as members said wednesday that the 
agreement provided nearly three times as much aid as the united 
states granted to deposed president ferdinand marcos 
our party is satisfied with the agreement and will support it 
although we realize that more hard work is needed to resolve other 
issues related to the american base facilities in our country 
the legislators said 
the senate created a special committee wednesday to determine if 
the new bases pact violates the philippine constitution and if the 
accord actually an amendment to a 47yearold agreement is 
subject to senate approval as some senators claim mrs aquino said 
it is not 
any extension beyond 1991 must be approved by twothirds of the 
senate where sentiment against the bases is strong 
the senates main objection to the accord is a provision that 
allows the united states to maintain its policy of neither 
confirming nor denying the presence of nuclear weapons on aircraft 
and ships visiting the bases 
the constitution mandates that the philippines adopt a policy of 
freedom from nuclear weapons consistent with the national 
interest but legal experts say the phrase falls short of an 
outright ban 
communist guerrillas whose demand for the removal of the bases 
has fanned a 20yearold rebellion accused the goverment of 
shamelessly selling out philippine sovereignty 
</TEXT>
