<TEXT>
a former elected official was 
sentenced to four life terms wednesday at the courthouse where he 
shot to death a judge a lawyer his former sisterinlaw and 
wounded his exwife 
clyde melvin 63 a former franklin county commissioner from 
nearby apalachicola pulled a 357caliber magnum revolver from his 
boot during a july 28 1987 alimony hearing at the gulf county 
courthouse and shot the victims before he was wounded in the neck 
by sheriff al harrison 
circuit judge carl harper of pensacola followed a jurys 93 
recommendation against sending melvin to floridas electric chair 
for the firstdegree murder of circuit judge wilson lamar bailey 
melvin was ordered to serve life in prison without parole for at 
least 25 years the only other sentence possible for that crime 
melvin was convicted sept 21 in pensacola of firstdegree 
murder for shooting bailey 64 of blountstown through the door of 
a bathroom where the judge had dashed for cover 
he also was convicted of attempted murder for shooting his 
exwife eleanor inez huckeba 60 in the head and seconddegree 
murder for the slayings of her lawyer tom ingles 43 of panama 
city and her sister peggy white paulk 55 of panama city beach 
melvins lawyer henry barksdale said he believed his client 
would be eligible for release when he is 88 upon serving the 
25year minimum for baileys slaying 
melvins trial was moved to pensacola because residents of this 
florida panhandle town where melvin had a career as a security 
guard at a paper mill knew too much about the case 
melvin and others were privately informed of the sentences 
before they were read in open court melvin remained seated and 
expressed no emotion except for a slight trembling of his cheeks 
and chin as the sentences were pronounced 
he declined an opportunity to make a statement 
several relatives of the victims were present all declined 
comment 
several psychologists and psychiatrists testified during his 
trial that melvin was paranoid and under great emotional distress 
at the time of the slayings they disagreed however on whether he 
was legally insane 
