<TEXT>
the teamsters union reacting to rankandfile 
repudiation of four of five of its biggest contracts this year is 
abolishing a decadesold practice requiring twothirds no votes 
to turn down tentative accords negotiated by its top leaders 
the change in the teamsters constitution requiring a simple 
majority any yes vote greater than 50 percent to approve 
contracts covering some 16 million members was approved wednesday 
by the unions 18member executive board meeting in greenelefe 
fla union sources said 
teamster dissidents and sources within the unions hierarchy 
said the decision was in response to a suit challenging a decision 
by top teamster officials in may to ignore a 635 percent 
membership rejection of a contract covering some 200000 interstate 
truck divers and warehouse workers 
the issue had been a major bone of contention in several 
contracts and in boston teamster leader william mccarthys victory 
over secretarytreasurer weldon mathis to succeed jackie presser as 
the unions president after pressers death in july 
duke zeller a teamster spokesman reached at greenelefe would 
not confirm or deny any changes in the unions constitution zeller 
said mccarthy planned to meet with representatives from 750 locals 
in chicago later this month to talk about new directions in the 
union 
however sources at greenelefe and at the unions headquarters 
here confirmed that the teamsters board had voted to do away with 
the twothirds membership vote requirement for turning down 
tentatively negotiated contracts 
other accords negotiated by teamster leaders but turned down by 
rankandfile majorities this year included tentative agreements 
signed with united parcel service rejected by 53 percent of the 
covered voting members and stroh brewery co rejected by 54 
percent 
a proposed contract covering some 20000 teamsters who drive 
auto transport trucks was renegotiated after it was rejected by 72 
percent on a first ratification vote in july results of a second 
ratification vote are due friday 
the only major contract approved by a majority of affected 
teamster members this year was with anheuserbusch cos covering 
some 9000 brewery workers 
ken paff an organizer for a 10000member dissident faction 
teamsters for a democratic union called the union boards action 
a major victory paff said teamster leaders agreed to the change as 
part of an attempt to work out a settlement to a suit his group 
filed last may in us district court here 
we have been fighting for this steadily for 12 years paff 
said they called us nuts and screwballs but we finally have 
majority rule in this union 
paff said the change had nothing to do with another suit by 
the justice department seeking to wrest control of the teamsters 
from its top officers on grounds they are controlled by organized 
crime 
that suit filed in us district court in manhattan last june 
would empower a courtappointed trustee to run the union mccarthy 
and other teamster leaders have denied that the union is controlled 
by mafia family heads as the justice departments suit alleges 
the feds have shown no interest in this its not a 
racketeering issue paff said of the former twothirds rule 
adopted in the 1950s when the late teamster president jimmy hoffa 
moved to seize control on contract decisions from union locals 
theres no law there has to be any membership vote on 
approving contracts paff said 
but the issue came to a boil in may when 635 percent of voting 
truck drivers and warehouse workers under the nationwide master 
freight agreement returned ballots rejecting a new threeyear 
contract 
mathis then acting as the unions president while presser was 
hospitalized with brain and lung cancer declared the contract 
ratified saying the twothirds requirement for rejecting it had 
not been met 
mccarthy and several other teamster leaders had campaigned 
against signing the accord and lobbied to reopen negotiations 
paff and officials within the unions hierarchy speaking on 
condition of anonymity said wednesday the new language requiring 
majority approval of new contacts instead of just 33 percent 
approval covers both nationwide and local accords negotiated 
separately by the teamsters 750 locals 
however they said it also includes a provision reverting to the 
twothirds rule if less than 50 percent of the affected members 
return ballots in any ratification vote 
meanwhile maurice schurr a teamster vice president and the 
unions top official in philadelphia the past decade retired 
wednesday from the 18member executive board amid a mccarthy move 
to oust him on charges of corruption 
schurr 75 agreed to retire effective nov 1 as the board was 
preparing to vote on internal union charges brought against him 
last month by mccarthy zeller said 
in july schurr had sided with mathis and against mccarthy head 
of the teamsters operations in new england for 20 years in the 
struggle for the unions leadership in the wake of pressers death 
schurr was convicted in june 1984 on charges of taking illegal 
payoffs from wholesale food employers with teamster contracts in 
the philadelphia area and served a brief prison sentence in 1986 
his conviction was repeatedly cited as an example of teamster 
corruption in the justice departments civil suit in june against 
the union 
