iran has withdrawn all its armed 
speedboats from a persian gulf island that was a major base for 
attacks on merchant shipping diplomatic sources said thursday 
the sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said 20 to 25 
speedboats were withdrawn recently from abu musa island in the 
southern gulf 
not a single speedboat is now in the vicinity of abu musa 
one source said 
the speedboats at abu musa were mainly swedishbuilt boghammar 
marin craft armed with machine guns rocketpropelled grenade 
launchers and antiaircraft cannon 
abu musa 30 miles off the coast of the united arab emirates 
was one of the principal bases for speedboat operations 
us and other foreign warships steered clear of the 12mile 
territorial limit claimed by iran around abu musa and other islands 
along the 600mile gulf 
iran has a speedboat base on farsi island in the northern gulf 
but shipping attacks from there ceased late last year and did not 
resume until just before a ceasefire took effect aug 20 in the 
iraniraq war 
since the ceasefire tehran has been trying to improve 
relations with its arab neighbors in the gulf and ease tensions in 
the waterway 
tehran has moved to normalize relations with kuwait which it 
accused of aiding iraq during the eightyear war 
irans parliament speaker hashemi rafsanjani has indicated 
tehran seeks to restore relations with saudi arabia which severed 
relations in april citing iranian subversion and terrorism 
there has been a decrease in iranian interceptions of merchant 
ships suspected of carrying warrelated materials to iraq 
the moves are seen as part of an effort by iran to appear more 
flexibile than iraq in peace talks aimed at ending the war the 
talks began in august but are deadlocked 
naval and shipping officials say there have been no iranian 
stopandsearch interceptions since the ceasefire took effect 
before that iranians were stopping scores of vessels each month 
iranian warships in the strait of hormuz the entry to the gulf 
still question commercial vessels by radio about their destinations 
and cargoes this is legal under maritime law until the warring 
nations sign a formal peace treaty 
some gulfbased shipping executives said these iranian radio 
interrogations have dropped to onethird of what they used to be 
the sources also said iranian warships are now seldom sighted in 
the southern gulf where they had been most active 
the iranians had fortified abu musa with tanks but these were 
withdrawn for use elsewhere in ground fighting us officers said 
recently 
