<TEXT>
one of the 41 million engines that powered 
the space shuttle discovery into orbit last month developed a small 
coolingsystem leak and will be replaced for the ships next flight 
in february the national aeronautics and space administration said 
thursday 
layers of nickel and copper from which the engines combustion 
chamber is fabricated were found to have separated in one area 
said jerry berg a spokesman at nasas marshall space flight center 
in alabama the leak resulted 
it is too early to tell whether the engine change will affect 
the flight schedule he said 
the problem was found during a postflight inspection wednesday 
at the kennedy space center in florida the engine will be removed 
and sent back to the manufacturer the rocketdyne division of 
rockwell international corp for repair 
its not possible to tell precisely when it happened said 
berg pressure tests were conducted before he flight and 
indicated the separation was not present 
berg said the leak did not show up on any of the instruments 
that monitored discoverys performance on the first flight since 
the challenger accident in january 1986 it only became apparent 
once we got into detailed inspection he said 
discovery completed its fourday onehour mission without a 
hitch landing at edwards air force base in california 
nasa officials said workers preparing discoverys sister ship 
for a late november flight will inspect an engine component on 
atlantis to make sure it was not damaged during preflight testing 
at the stennis space center in bay st louis miss 
officials were uncertain how the developments would effect 
launch dates for atlantis scheduled to fly no earlier than nov 23 
the atlantis inspection was ordered after an engine being tested 
for use on space shuttle columbia sustained damage said conrad 
nagel who is in charge of preparations for the second 
postchallenger mission 
we have no reason to believe weve got a problem nagel 
said but we had a problem on another engine and theyve asked us 
to go back and look at it on ours 
space shuttles are propelled into orbit by two solidfuel rocket 
boosters that drop off when they are spent and by three engines 
that are fed supercool liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen from the 
shuttles huge fuel tank 
nasa meanwhile appointed a board to investigate the fire that 
damaged the magellan spacecraft during a power systems check on 
monday night the fire resulted when a technician for spacecraft 
builder martin marietta corp forced an electrical plug into the 
wrong receptacle 
the damage to the spacecraft which is to conduct an eightmonth 
mapping mission of venus is not expected to affect the april 1989 
launch date 
