<TEXT>
smurfs the lovable blue gnomes with 
four fingers and a special language were born in 1958 when a 
preoccupied cartoonist called peyo asked a friend to pass the salt 
but said schtroumpf instead 
three decades after they appeared as minor characters in a 
belgian series on knights and kings they are among the worlds 
favorite cartoon characters 
their adventures have been told in 13 books translated into 25 
languages they have appeared in 250 smurf television programs and 
four featurelength movies 
a smurf is a pitufo in spanish the original schtroumpf in 
french a schlumpf in german and smolf in danish italians call 
them puffos and to the japanese they are sumafus a smurf is a nam 
ching ling to the chinese and the hebrew word is dardassim 
all this has brought fame and fortune to peyo who in real life 
is pierre culliford a 60yearold native of brussels who now lives 
in switzerland 
he is grateful and threw a smurfday party oct 16 in the belgian 
capitals historic grand place square attended by about 5000 
children and adults 
i feel a bit groggy he said looking out at the crowd 
the party featured a giant cake drawing contests puppet shows 
a magician and replicas of the smurfs toadstool homes in a 
setting of some of the finest gothic and baroque architecture in 
europe 
cullifords slip of the tongue in 1958 created an industry 
smurfs now appear on 2000 consumer products around the world from 
writing gear to mugs knapsacks to sweatshirts spaghetti packages 
and yogurt jars to petroleum products 
unauthorized uses have included an appearance on the sides of 
water cannon trucks used by panamanian security forces 
we know about that from a belgian television crew that was 
filming in panama but we have not authorized the smurfs to be used 
in that form said nadine peeters of imps the brussels agency 
that approves commercial use of the smurfs 
the cuddly culliford creations use the word smurf both as verb 
and noun in a language that can be confusing but at times is rich 
in poetic harmony 
educators once scorned the strange tongue which children 
usually understand better than adults but it gradually won 
acceptance and even appears in an official dutch dictionary 
early on parents complained because their kids started to 
talk smurfish peyo said at the giant birthday party but now 
he is planning a 60acre smurf entertainment park near metz 
france a smurf monthly magazine and a 14th book about an 
ambitious smurf who wants to open a bank 
much of the smurf surge of recent years is attributable to their 
appearance on television and development of the us market 
when peyo spent that evening with a fellow cartoonist at seaside 
restaurant 30 years ago he was drawing johan and pirlouit a 
cartoon series set in the middle ages 
he wanted to introduce gnomes of which he was fond but most 
of them are too scary or immoral to feature in cartoons for kids 
the dinnertable gaffe gave him the smurfs with their funny 
language and they caught on quickly 
first came their own strip then books and in 1975 the first 
smurf movie the flute with the six smurfs 
plastic and stuffed smurfs reached the united states in 1978 
four years later an estimated 9 million youngsters were watching 
them on saturday morning television 
cullifordpeyo gives this explanation of their success the 
smurfs do not fit into any category every culture can absorb the 
smurfs because the smurfs do not belong to any culture everybody 
understands the blue gnomes 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

