<TEXT>
cartoon movies are a universal hit with 
youngsters peter dalglish reasoned so that should be the best way 
to teach street kids of the world the perils of aids 
the canadian youth workers short animated film survivors is 
being made on a budget of 500000 415000 us by the national 
film board of canada whose awardwinning experience with animation 
dates back nearly five decades 
it should be ready for distribution in 20 languages by the time 
more than 10000 health workers and other experts gather in 
montreal next june for the fifth international conference on aids 
for which no cure has been found 
were trying to reach kids in the 30 largest cities of the 
developing world dalglish 31 said in an interview its a 
film for the front lines i think were two or three years ahead of 
the game 
a preliminary version of the cartoon without music or full 
animation has been tested on young audiences in the philippines 
kenya sri lanka brazil and new york 
we saw very strong identification with the characters 
dalglish said the story tested extremely well 
dalglish went to africa after finishing law school and in 
khartoum sudan founded street kids international which forms 
bicycle courier services to provide jobs it now employs 20 
children at any given time and is planning expansion to other 
cities with capital raised in canada 
you have to be able to provide an alternative to 
prostitution dalglish said given a choice theyll all choose 
riding a bicycle over sleeping with someone 
in khartoum he became increasingly concerned about the 
potential for disaster as aids becomes a disease concentrated among 
the urban poor 
acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that 
damages the bodys immune system leaving victims susceptible to 
infections and cancer 
it is spread most often through sexual contact needles or 
syringes shared by drug abusers infected blood or blood products 
and from pregnant women to their offspring 
canada has reported more than 2000 aids cases and estimates for 
1992 run up to 12000 but the scene of survivors is 
specifically third world depicting children picking pockets or 
turning to prostitution 
no reliable estimates are available of how prevalent aids has 
become among street children who may number 40 million throughout 
the world but dalglish said the prevalence of other sexually 
transmitted diseases might make the projections pessimistic 
he said the idea of an animated film was born in khartoum when 
he borrowed a projector from the us embassy to show his 
youngsters a tom and jerry cartoon and for the first time that 
anyone could remember we had the complete attention of every kid in 
the room 
survivors is intended for showing to small groups of 
children aged 6 to 14 with a youth worker present to lead a 
discussion afterward 
it makes it easy for kids to talk about aids about health 
with street workers dalglish said we could be subtle while 
being reasonably explicit at the same time 
he hopes to raise funds for accompanying instruction guides and 
comic books 
dalglish and the production team went to mexico and guatemala so 
the animators could get to know their audience and create an 
authentic atmosphere but the setting is intentionally vague in 
order to broaden the films appeal 
even new york street kids were intrigued by it dalglish said 
but survivors is not really intended for those raised on 
saturday morning cartoons 
the canadian hopes explicit language in the film and instruction 
about the use of condoms will not create barriers to its 
distribution 
we are recognizing the reality that exists in the street and 
responding to it he said the kids see it as a moral film 
end adv for thur pms oct 27 
