<TEXT>
while politics and economics are entwined 
inextricably they are hardly supportive of each other 
they speak different languages they communicate differently 
political practitioners often take great liberties with the 
facts and so confuse voters but economists create equal confusion 
by concentrating on esoteric data that mean nothing to anyone 
they cannot live without each other but they live poorly 
together 
economic thinkers complain that practical politicians distort 
sound economic ideas political thinkers say economists dont 
understand the real world 
the relationship is sometimes even destructive 
politicians often are misled by faulty economic advice 
president gerald ford for instance launched a campaign to fight 
inflation when inflation was waning and recession was becoming the 
big problem 
and it is also true that economists may be damaged by 
politicians the former it is often said lose their objectivity 
on the day they accept a political appointment some cannot return 
to their old academic jobs 
americans are now getting a wretched dose of this fractious 
relationship as the two presidential candidates expel figures and 
facts that cannot be understood are out of context or cannot 
be verified 
as a consequence it is nearly impossible to determine the 
economic state of the united states from the political platforms or 
performances 
here are some of the broader gauges and a middleoftheroad 
assessment 
the gross national product broadest indicator of economic 
strength or weakness rose from 424 trillion in 1986 to 45 
trillion in 1987 and will reach a projected 486 trillion in 1988 
assessment steady moderate growth anything stronger might 
mean inflation weaker growth might be equally unacceptable with a 
pervasive threat of recession 
the federal deficit averaged about 144 billion in the fiscal 
year ended sept 30 a sizeable improvement from deficits of 213 
billion in 1986 and 163 billion in 1987 
assessment they are still horrendously high moreover it is 
still uncertain that the underlying problems have been resolved or 
that the trend to improvement will continue 
the trade deficit is running at a rate of less than 100 
billion its lowest since the winter of 1985 
assessment it too remains extremely high with no certainty 
that the improvement will continue american exports particularly 
of manufactured goods have been improving but imports surged 
recently 
inflation using the gross national product as a base has been 
rising from 27 percent in 1986 to 33 percent in 1987 and a bit 
more than that in 1988 
assessment rising inflation is always a threat and many 
economists fear it is a major one in 1989 but earlier worries 
about inflation have been overdone 
moreover the strongest inflation is in the consumer rather than 
producing sectors manufacturing competition now firmly on a 
global scale is keeping those price increases relatively low 
employment has been rising steadily from 1096 million in 1986 
to 1124 million in 1987 to perhaps 115 million in 1988 
unemployment has been dropping from 7 percent in 1986 to 62 
percent in 1987 to about 55 percent this year 
assessment strong figures but potentially an economic threat 
fears exist that the falling jobless rate eventually will put 
upward pressure on prices 
so far however there is little evidence that any such process 
has begun wages in fact have been unusually steady discounted 
for inflation income has grown but so has production so far it 
isnt an inflation scenario 
the consensus of forecasters seems to be that prospects for 
recession in 1989 are slim at least in the first half of the year 
assessment such forecasts are good for six months less so for 
a year and perhaps meangingless beyond that no good economist 
these days will ever make a forecast without citing the possibility 
of recession within a couple of years 
the reason for this is simply that the economic expansion has 
gone on for six years well beyond expectations and therefore may 
be vulnerable some time soon again strong statistical evidence of 
recession hasnt shown up yet 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

